1 61-35-09. Bylaws submitted at special meeting.
2 Within thirty days after election of the original board, proposed bylaws must be submitted
3 for adoption at a special meeting of members of the district, written notice of which must be
4 mailed to each member. Members present at the special meeting may adopt or amend any of
5 the proposed bylaws, and may propose and adopt alternative or additional bylaws by a majority
6 vote. The bylaws may subsequently be amended at any annual or special meeting of the
7 participating members of the district. However, the bylaws of each district must provide:
8 1. For an annual meeting of participating members each year after the year of
9 organization of the district and for mailing of written notice of the time and place of
10 each annual meeting to each participating member and publication of the notice in the
11 official newspaper of the county or counties served by the district not less than ten nor
12 more than thirty days before each meeting.
13 2. That each participating member of the district is entitled to one vote at all annual and
14 special meetings of the district for each benefit unit to which the member has
15 subscribed.
16 3. That each participating member seeking election to the board shall present a petition
17 containing signatures of ten participating members. All petitions must be submitted to
18 the secretary of the board or nominating committee at least forty - five days before the
19 election or by the mail election deadline established under the district's bylaws. Any
20 participating member who submits a petition must be added to the ballot, provided
21 they reside in the appropriate district and qualify to serve as a director under the
22 district's bylaws.
23 SECTION 4. AMENDMENT. Section 61-35-10 of the North Dakota Century Code is
24 amended and reenacted as follows:
25 61-35-10. Directors divided into classes - Terms - Vacancies.
26 1. The initial board of each district shall divide its members by lot into three classes of as
27 nearly equal size as possible. The terms of the directors in the first, second, and third
28 classes expire on dates of the annual meetings in the first, second, and third years,
29 respectively, following the year in which the district is organized, or as soon thereafter
30 as their successors are elected and have qualified.
